column2: Howard Pyle's radio broadcast of the surrender ceremony at Baguio City, Philippines. Known as the "Tiger of Malaya," Yamashita surrendered in the presence of Generals Jonathan Wainwright and Arthur Percival, who were previously imprisoned by the Japanese in Manchuria. Pyle said he was the only news correspondent to cover the Japanese surrender on board the USS Missouri and Yamashita's surrender at Baguio City.
column32: "General Yamashita Surrender Ceremony," Howard Pyle Collection, 1988-00115A, Arizona State University Library.

column2: Interviews with Mucio Delgado regarding conference proceedings and Argentinian representation.  Topics discussed include Arizonans and Argentina trade relations and beef imports.  In 1941, Mucio F. Delgado, program manager with the Prescott radio station KYTA, met Nelson Rockefeller, Assistant Secretary of State for Latin American Affairs, at a meeting of the Inter-American Affairs in San Francisco. At that time, Jimmy Creasman was Delgado’s counterpart and friend. In this interview in 1945, Delgado was a representative of the IAA in New York and no longer lived in Arizona. Because of his work as a representative for the IAA, he was probably familiar with FDR’s Good Neighbor Policy and his intent to foster better relations with US allies in Latin America and Mexico.
